Use MAUI's `#if` platform preprocessor directives inside `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- Place each implementation under `Platforms/<OS>/` (e.g., `Platforms/Android/AndroidNotificationService.cs`).
- The preprocessor symbols (`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`) are defined automatically per target framework — only the matching branch compiles for each platform, so there's no runtime risk of a missing type.
- Use `AddSingleton`, `AddTransient`, or `AddScoped` depending on your lifetime needs.
- Inject `INotificationService` via constructor injection anywhere in your app.
